ANALYTICS PROJECT

Principal Components Analysis

This computer lab provides a few simulated and empirical examples to explore Principal Components Analysis (PCA). The first exercise explores the properties of PCA via simulation, while the remaining exercises applies PCA to several empirical datasets.

The first principal component in our example therefore explains 55.5% of the variability, and the second principal component explains 20.4%. Together, the first two principal components explain 75.9% of the variability.

By examining the principal component vectors above, we can infer the: + the first principal component (PC1) roughly corresponds to levels 3,4 and 3+4. + The second component (PC2) is affected by level 2 more than the other 4 variables, so it roughly corresponds to the influence of level 2

The sample PCAs are:

\[\hat{Y}_1= 0.318 level 1 -0.492 level 3 - 0.552 level 4 - 0.592 level(3+4) \]

\[\hat{Y}_2= 0.381 level 1 - 0.909 level 2 + 0.157 level 3 \]

\[\hat{Y}_3= 0.767 level 1 + 0.414 level 2 + 0.453 level 3 + 0.160 level (3+4) \]

\[\hat{Y}_4= 0.407 level 1 - 0.616 level 3 + 0.663 level 4 + 0.115 level (3+4)\] \[\hat{Y}_5= 0.384 level 3 + 0.493 level 4 - 0.780 level (3+4)\]
